 Army, and the Navy, Martin L. Cook finds a powerful but underappreciated basis for military ethics in the oath to the Constitution that members of the armed services pledge. In Issues in Military Ethics, Cook considers the role of airpower in counterinsurgency war and the place of robotic weapons systems on the battlefield, but he also looks beyond ethics in the conduct of war to issues arising in military life generally. He addresses a range of other issues with pressing contemporary relevance, including civil-military relations, ethics education, and religion, in particular the ascendency of evangelical Christianity in military culture. This volume serves as an important resource for scholars, members of the armed services, and educators alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCivil-military relations -- United States. 0aCivil-military relationszUnited States. 0aMilitary education -- Moral and ethical aspects -- United States. 0aMilitary educationxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 0aMilitary ethics -- United States. 0aMilitary ethicszUnited States. 0aMilitary service, Voluntary -- United States. 0aMilitary service, VoluntaryzUnited States. 0aUnited States -- Armed Forces -- Religious life. 0aWar -- Moral and ethical aspects. 0aWarxMoral and ethical aspects. 4aPhilosophy : Ethics. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPolitics and Law : International Relations. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aConversino, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSyse, Henrik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUlrich, Mary Beth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 20